            "contents": [
                {
                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                    "type": "section",
                    "ref": "orgc31c939",
                    "properties": {
                        "post-blank": 1,
                        "post-affiliated": 640
                    },
                    "contents": [
                        {
                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                            "type": "paragraph",
                            "ref": "org7167807",
                            "properties": {
                                "post-blank": 0,
                                "post-affiliated": 640
                            },
                            "contents": [
                                "The classical way in which a modeller picks the complexity of the model\n(s)he will fit is by bearing the following plot in mind:\n",
                                {
                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                    "type": "link",
                                    "ref": "org7240bd9",
                                    "properties": {
                                        "type": "file",
                                        "path": "/images/u-shaped-curve.png",
                                        "format": "bracket",
                                        "raw-link": "/images/u-shaped-curve.png",
                                        "application": null,
                                        "search-option": null,
                                        "post-blank": 0,
                                        "is-internal": false,
                                        "target-ref": null,
                                        "is-inline-image": true
                                    },
                                    "contents": []
                                },
                                "\n"
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                    "type": "headline",
                    "ref": "org4e06340",
                    "drawer": {},
                    "properties": {
                        "tags-all": [],
                        "raw-value": "",
                        "pre-blank": 0,
                        "level": 2,
                        "priority": null,
                        "tags": [],
                        "todo-keyword": null,
                        "todo-type": null,
                        "post-blank": 1,
                        "footnote-section-p": false,
                        "archivedp": false,
                        "commentedp": false,
                        "post-affiliated": 801,
                        "title": [
                            ""
                        ]
                    },
                    "contents": [
                        {
                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                            "type": "section",
                            "ref": "org9bd5d35",
                            "properties": {
                                "post-blank": 1,
                                "post-affiliated": 805
                            },
                            "contents": [
                                {
                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                    "type": "paragraph",
                                    "ref": "org2ad4368",
                                    "properties": {
                                        "post-blank": 0,
                                        "post-affiliated": 805
                                    },
                                    "contents": [
                                        "Here it's easy to see that there's a point from which on increasing\ncomplexity translates to degrading test performance. In the classical\nscenario, model complexity is tuned to be close to the minimum of this\nU-shaped curve: the sweet-spot between having enough expressiveness to\nfit closely enough to the training data, and not being too expressive so\nas to not simply memorize the training data (what's commonly called\n",
                                        {
                                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                            "type": "bold",
                                            "ref": "org8ed4443",
                                            "properties": {
                                                "post-blank": 0
                                            },
                                            "contents": [
                                                "overfitting"
                                            ]
                                        },
                                        ").\n"
                                    ]
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                    "type": "headline",
                    "ref": "orgc5f6873",
                    "drawer": {},
                    "properties": {
                        "tags-all": [],
                        "raw-value": "",
                        "pre-blank": 0,
                        "level": 2,
                        "priority": null,
                        "tags": [],
                        "todo-keyword": null,
                        "todo-type": null,
                        "post-blank": 1,
                        "footnote-section-p": false,
                        "archivedp": false,
                        "commentedp": false,
                        "post-affiliated": 1243,
                        "title": [
                            ""
                        ]
                    },
                    "contents": [
                        {
                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                            "type": "section",
                            "ref": "org123703b",
                            "properties": {
                                "post-blank": 1,
                                "post-affiliated": 1247
                            },
                            "contents": [
                                {
                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                    "type": "paragraph",
                                    "ref": "orgf5562dc",
                                    "properties": {
                                        "post-blank": 0,
                                        "post-affiliated": 1247
                                    },
                                    "contents": [
                                        "However, in the era of Deep Learning, the case is, more often than not,\nthat we have extremely complex models - where the number of parameters\nis much larger than the number of training samples - which are almost\nperfectly fitted to training data, reaching very low training error, and\nare still able to generalize. This contradicts the classical view, and\nstill requires a complete theoretical explanation. Prof.\u00a0Belkin's work\nis a very interesting step in the direction of that explanation.\n"
                                    ]
                                }
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                    "type": "headline",
                    "ref": "org1f35ab8",
                    "drawer": {},
                    "properties": {
                        "tags-all": [],
                        "raw-value": "",
                        "pre-blank": 0,
                        "level": 2,
                        "priority": null,
                        "tags": [],
                        "todo-keyword": null,
                        "todo-type": null,
                        "post-blank": 0,
                        "footnote-section-p": false,
                        "archivedp": false,
                        "commentedp": false,
                        "post-affiliated": 1741,
                        "title": [
                            ""
                        ]
                    },
                    "contents": [
                        {
                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                            "type": "section",
                            "ref": "org94ba092",
                            "properties": {
                                "post-blank": 1,
                                "post-affiliated": 1745
                            },
                            "contents": [
                                {
                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                    "type": "paragraph",
                                    "ref": "org2b07087",
                                    "properties": {
                                        "post-blank": 0,
                                        "post-affiliated": 1745
                                    },
                                    "contents": [
                                        "The paper's central idea is that there is another regime, classically\nnot considered, after the interpolation threshold of model complexity\n(for many models this just means having at least as many parameters as\ndata points). From this point on, models are able to perfectly fit the\ntraining data, but their test risk starts decreasing again, which\ncreates what the paper describes as a \"double descent curve\":\n",
                                        {
                                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                            "type": "link",
                                            "ref": "org2a4689b",
                                            "properties": {
                                                "type": "file",
                                                "path": "/images/double-descent-curve.png",
                                                "format": "bracket",
                                                "raw-link": "/images/double-descent-curve.png",
                                                "application": null,
                                                "search-option": null,
                                                "post-blank": 0,
                                                "is-internal": false,
                                                "target-ref": null,
                                                "is-inline-image": true
                                            },
                                            "contents": []
                                        },
                                        "\n"
                                    ]
                                }
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                            "type": "headline",
                            "ref": "org5f08870",
                            "drawer": {},
                            "properties": {
                                "tags-all": [],
                                "raw-value": "",
                                "pre-blank": 0,
                                "level": 3,
                                "priority": null,
                                "tags": [],
                                "todo-keyword": null,
                                "todo-type": null,
                                "post-blank": 1,
                                "footnote-section-p": false,
                                "archivedp": false,
                                "commentedp": false,
                                "post-affiliated": 2193,
                                "title": [
                                    ""
                                ]
                            },
                            "contents": [
                                {
                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                    "type": "section",
                                    "ref": "org89ace59",
                                    "properties": {
                                        "post-blank": 1,
                                        "post-affiliated": 2198
                                    },
                                    "contents": [
                                        {
                                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                            "type": "paragraph",
                                            "ref": "org338a96e",
                                            "properties": {
                                                "post-blank": 0,
                                                "post-affiliated": 2198
                                            },
                                            "contents": [
                                                "But why would this happen? The first thing to notice is that, after the\ninterpolation threshold, the training error basically drops to zero,\nregardless of the number of parameters: so clearly Empirical Risk\nMinimization stops being a proxy for the true performance. According to\nthe paper, the answer lies in the appropriate definition of the\ninductive bias associated with each problem. They suggest that a\nfunction-space norm (i.e., a norm defined over a space of functions -\ne.g., the $l",
                                                {
                                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                                    "type": "subscript",
                                                    "ref": "org0bdd254",
                                                    "properties": {
                                                        "use-brackets-p": false,
                                                        "post-blank": 0
                                                    },
                                                    "contents": [
                                                        "2"
                                                    ]
                                                },
                                                "$-norm of the parameter vector of a parametric family) can\nbe an appropriate proxy for the inductive bias. The punchline is that a\nvector with more elements can have a smaller norm than a vector with\nfewer elements, so if that norm is an actual measure of the simplicity\n(regularity) of the learned function, it's possible that we can access\nsimpler (more regular) learned functions with more complex model\nfamilies. The paper claims that using such a norm in this manner\nconstitutes a form of Occam's razor.\n"
                                            ]
                                        }
                                    ]
                                }
                            ]
                        },
                        {
                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                            "type": "headline",
                            "ref": "org9846d94",
                            "drawer": {},
                            "properties": {
                                "tags-all": [],
                                "raw-value": "",
                                "pre-blank": 0,
                                "level": 3,
                                "priority": null,
                                "tags": [],
                                "todo-keyword": null,
                                "todo-type": null,
                                "post-blank": 0,
                                "footnote-section-p": false,
                                "archivedp": false,
                                "commentedp": false,
                                "post-affiliated": 3200,
                                "title": [
                                    ""
                                ]
                            },
                            "contents": [
                                {
                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                    "type": "section",
                                    "ref": "org4b5fc05",
                                    "properties": {
                                        "post-blank": 0,
                                        "post-affiliated": 3205
                                    },
                                    "contents": [
                                        {
                                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                            "type": "paragraph",
                                            "ref": "org57ca8e0",
                                            "properties": {
                                                "post-blank": 1,
                                                "post-affiliated": 3205
                                            },
                                            "contents": [
                                                "The paper presents empiricial evidence for these claims using a\nparametric model. They fit the model in the classical regime, and in the\n\"modern\" regime, varying the number of parameters ",
                                                {
                                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                                    "type": "latex-fragment",
                                                    "ref": "orgd383e90",
                                                    "properties": {
                                                        "value": "$n$",
                                                        "post-blank": 0
                                                    },
                                                    "contents": []
                                                },
                                                ". For each ",
                                                {
                                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                                    "type": "latex-fragment",
                                                    "ref": "orgf643945",
                                                    "properties": {
                                                        "value": "$n$",
                                                        "post-blank": 0
                                                    },
                                                    "contents": []
                                                },
                                                ",\ngiven solutions which yield the same training error, they choose the one\nwith the smallest $l",
                                                {
                                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                                    "type": "subscript",
                                                    "ref": "org49214fd",
                                                    "properties": {
                                                        "use-brackets-p": false,
                                                        "post-blank": 0
                                                    },
                                                    "contents": [
                                                        "2"
                                                    ]
                                                },
                                                "$-norm. Doing so they obtain the predicted \"double\ndescent curve\". Moreover, they plot the value of the solution's\n$l",
                                                {
                                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                                    "type": "subscript",
                                                    "ref": "orgb9b4a42",
                                                    "properties": {
                                                        "use-brackets-p": false,
                                                        "post-blank": 0
                                                    },
                                                    "contents": [
                                                        "2"
                                                    ]
                                                },
                                                "$-norm for each ",
                                                {
                                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                                    "type": "latex-fragment",
                                                    "ref": "org5b6ac97",
                                                    "properties": {
                                                        "value": "$n$",
                                                        "post-blank": 0
                                                    },
                                                    "contents": []
                                                },
                                                ", and it decreases as predicted after the\ninterpolation threshold: ",
                                                {
                                                    "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                                    "type": "link",
                                                    "ref": "org43a3346",
                                                    "properties": {
                                                        "type": "file",
                                                        "path": "/images/rff-belkin.png",
                                                        "format": "bracket",
                                                        "raw-link": "/images/rff-belkin.png",
                                                        "application": null,
                                                        "search-option": null,
                                                        "post-blank": 0,
                                                        "is-internal": false,
                                                        "target-ref": null,
                                                        "is-inline-image": true
                                                    },
                                                    "contents": []
                                                },
                                                "\n"
                                            ]
                                        },
                                        {
                                            "$$data_type": "org-node",
                                            "type": "paragraph",
                                            "ref": "org6d3465c",
                                            "properties": {
                                                "post-blank": 0,
                                                "post-affiliated": 3739
                                            },
                                            "contents": [
                                                "I found these ideas extremely interesting, and invite everyone to read\nthe paper.\n"
                                            ]
                                        }
